<Project>
  <PropertyGroup>
    <TargetFramework>net10.0</TargetFramework>
    <Nullable>enable</Nullable>
    <ImplicitUsings>enable</ImplicitUsings>
    <LangVersion>latest</LangVersion>
    <InvariantGlobalization>true</InvariantGlobalization>
    <!-- AngleSharp.Css 0.17.0 declares a dependency on AngleSharp 0.17.x, but this solution
         resolves AngleSharp 1.5.1 (needed elsewhere — HtmlImportSanitizer,
         OpenXmlToHtmlConverter, etc.). Verified directly, not assumed: cascade/specificity/
         inheritance resolution all work correctly on 1.5.1 (see eBookEditor.Html's own csproj
         comment). The only true 1.x-targeting AngleSharp.Css release is an unstable prerelease
         that throws at runtime computing em/% font sizes — worse than this warning. -->
    <NoWarn>$(NoWarn);NU1608</NoWarn>
    <!-- Bump the minor version for new features, patch for other code changes (see
         feedback_version_bump_policy memory). This round adds Kindle/KDP support to EPUB
         export (landmarks nav + fixed cover meta), fixes a Markdig delimiter-char bug that
         made PDF/Word misread strikethrough/highlight/subscript/superscript/definition
         lists as bold or italic, wires up Markdown Extra heading id/class attributes and
         custom containers, and adds a right-click "Apply Style" editor menu backed by ten
         curated CSS styles — all new features (plus one bug fix bundled into the same
         release), so a minor bump. -->
    <!-- 1.9.1: user-reported bug fixes, no new features, so a patch bump. Word export
         produced schema-invalid .docx whenever a table was present (missing <w:tblGrid>,
         <w:tblBorders> children in the wrong order) or a run combined underline+highlight
         (<w:highlight>/<w:u> also wrong order) — Word/Pages refused to open the file at all
         ("isn't in the correct format"), not just render it wrong. Also fixed a gap in the
         editor-blank-on-Edit bug: switching directly between two chapters while already in
         Edit mode changed CurrentText without ever changing Mode, so it missed the existing
         Mode-changed redraw fix entirely; that existing fix was also hardened to force a full
         Document.Text reset rather than relying on a bare TextView.Redraw() call. -->
    <!-- 1.9.2: another user-reported bug fix, no new features. Chapter links on the in-book
         EPUB Table of Contents page rendered as literal "[text](url)" text instead of clickable
         links, because chapter filenames ("NNN - Title.md") contain spaces and CommonMark link
         destinations can't contain unescaped spaces without angle brackets — Markdig silently
         fell back to literal text, and EpubInternalLinkResolver's own regex had the same
         space-blindness so it never even got a chance to rewrite the link to the real EPUB
         content filename. Front/back matter links (title-page.md, imprint.md, etc.) have no
         spaces, so only chapter entries were affected — easy to miss without a real chapter in
         the test fixtures, which is exactly why the existing EpubBuilderTests hadn't caught it. -->
    <!-- 1.9.3: four more user-reported bug fixes from the same round of real-world testing,
         no new features. (1) Word export was STILL corrupt after 1.9.1's schema-order fix,
         for a different reason: hyperlinks to chapter paths containing spaces
         ("chapters/001 - Getting Ready.md") were fed straight into
         AddHyperlinkRelationship as unescaped URIs, which the OpenXml SDK's own package layer
         flags as malformed — in practice this baked a literal "rewritten://<guid>" placeholder
         into the saved file's actual relationship target, which Word rightly refused to open.
         Fixed by percent-encoding link destinations before they reach AddHyperlinkRelationship.
         A second, deeper cause of the same symptom turned up testing against the user's actual
         project: when a link's destination fails to parse (the space case above), CommonMark
         can resolve "[text](broken url)" as a shortcut reference instead — and Markdig's
         AutoIdentifier extension implicitly registers every heading as a reference target under
         its own text, so a TOC entry whose text matches a later chapter heading resolves that
         way. LinkInline.Url comes back empty for that case; the real URL lives behind
         GetDynamicUrl. Reading only .Url fed an empty string into AddHyperlinkRelationship —
         fixed by resolving GetDynamicUrl first and falling back to plain (non-hyperlinked) text
         if that's empty too, in both the Word and PDF renderers.
         (2) PDF table-of-contents page numbers rendered as a literal "?" for any empty/unwritten
         chapter (a "New Chapter" stub), and the running header got stuck showing the previous
         chapter's name for the rest of the book — both caused by QuestPDF's .Section() only
         ever being attached to a chapter's first rendered content block, which several block
         types bypassed entirely and an empty chapter never reached at all. Fixed by registering
         the section via an unconditional zero-height marker, decoupled from content shape.
         (3) Further hardened the editor-blank-on-Edit fix: the redraw was still running
         synchronously inside the Mode-changed handler, before Avalonia necessarily finished
         laying out the just-revealed control with a real size — deferred via
         Dispatcher.UIThread.Post so it runs after layout catches up. (4) DOCX import: a
         "Table of Contents" section (Word-field-generated or hand-typed) listing chapter
         titles was previously indistinguishable from real chapter headings by text alone, so
         each entry became its own bogus, empty chapter — now recognized and skipped. -->
    <!-- 1.10.0: new feature, so a minor bump — and the definitive fix for the editor-blank
         bug that 1.9.1/1.9.3 kept patching around without fully curing. The user reported it
         was still happening after both fixes, which pointed at the real problem: AvaloniaEdit
         going IsVisible=False (whenever Preview mode was toggled on) let its cached visual
         lines go stale in ways that redraw-on-reveal could only ever paper over, not prevent.
         Removed the whole-pane Edit/Preview toggle entirely — the editor is now always visible,
         so that entire class of bug can't recur — and replaced it with an "Open Preview" button
         that opens a standalone PreviewWindow (Markdown.Avalonia), kept in sync with the
         editor's content and, approximately (proportional line-fraction, not an exact source
         mapping), the cursor's position as you type or switch chapters. EditorViewModel lost
         its Mode/PreviewSource/TogglePreviewCommand entirely; generated pages (title/imprint/
         TOC/about-author) no longer force Preview on open since there's no mode to force
         anymore — their raw Markdown is just always visible like any other page's, same as
         everything else, with rendering available on demand via the same Open Preview button. -->
    <!-- 1.10.1: THE actual fix for the editor-blank bug — a patch bump since it's a bug fix,
         no new feature. Every attempt through 1.10.0 (redraw timing, dispatcher deferral,
         removing the whole-pane Preview toggle) was chasing the wrong cause: the user reported
         the editor was STILL empty even with the toggle gone entirely, which is what it took to
         rule out visibility-toggling as the cause at all. The real bug: App.axaml never merged
         AvaloniaEditCore's own theme resources (no StyleInclude anywhere referencing them), so
         the vendored TextEditor control had no ControlTheme registered — meaning no
         ControlTemplate, meaning it rendered as a completely empty, template-less area
         regardless of Document content, regardless of visibility, regardless of any redraw
         timing. Confirmed by reading the vendored source directly: TextEditor.xaml (its
         ControlTheme) is merged into Themes/Base.xaml via MergeResourceInclude, which is in
         turn merged into Themes/Fluent/AvaloniaEdit.xaml (a <Styles> file) — the one line
         missing from App.axaml the whole time. Added
         <StyleInclude Source="avares://AvaloniaEditCore/Themes/Fluent/AvaloniaEdit.xaml" />
         to Application.Styles. -->
    <!-- 1.11.0: new feature, so a minor bump. Adds a right-click "Insert Image…" editor menu
         item: picks a file (starting in the project's images/ folder, created if missing),
         copies it in if it wasn't already there, and inserts it with a caption styled by a new
         "Caption" entry in EditorStyleCatalog (half-size, italic — added to both
         DefaultStylesheet.cs and "Vellum Serif.css", with a new EditorStyleCatalogTests
         asserting every catalog class has a matching rule in both, closing the loop on "do
         these actually exist in the stylesheet"). The image+caption markup is deliberately
         nested custom containers, not a Markdown table: verified directly against the Markdig
         pipeline that a trailing "{.class}" attribute block immediately after a pipe table
         makes the whole table fail to parse and fall back to literal pipe-character text — not
         documented anywhere, just how the parser behaves. Auditing whether Apply Style's
         existing ten classes (now eleven) actually render in the Open Preview window (the
         other half of this round's request) turned up a real, separate gap: Markdown.Avalonia
         is an independent parser, not Markdig, with no support at all for custom containers or
         attribute blocks — both rendered as visibly broken raw-syntax text there. Added
         PreviewMarkdownSanitizer (eBookEditor.Markdown) to strip both before handing content to
         the preview, verified end-to-end against the real Markdown.Avalonia engine via a
         headless Avalonia harness (not just unit-tested in isolation) — Preview now shows clean
         plain text/images instead of broken syntax, though still without the actual CSS-driven
         styling, since Preview has no CSS engine of its own regardless. -->
    <!-- 2.0.0: marks the start of the Markdown → HTML content-model refactor (major bump, per
         explicit user instruction, since this is a breaking change to the project file format
         itself, not an incremental feature/fix). No code changes in this commit — chapters are
         still Markdown; this bump exists purely to mark the plan's adoption point in history
         before implementation begins. See Docs/html-refactor-plan.md (originally authored at
         /Users/admin/.claude/plans/dapper-hugging-lighthouse.md, copied into the repo so it
         ships with the source it describes) for the full phased plan: HTML-native chapter
         storage (new .ebhtml extension), an
         AngleSharp-driven HTML DOM replacing Markdig's AST across EPUB/PDF/Word export, a
         WebView-based (Avalonia.Controls.WebView) WYSIWYG editor mode alongside raw HTML
         editing, a matching WebView-based Preview window, and eventual removal of the vendored
         AvaloniaEdit copy once Markdown.Avalonia (the reason it was vendored) is gone. Each
         phase gets its own minor bump, commit, and push as it lands. -->
    <!-- 2.1.0: Phase 0 of the HTML refactor (see 2.0.0 note / the plan doc) — the WebView
         spike. No production code changes; a standalone Avalonia.Controls.WebView +
         contenteditable proof of concept (outside this repo, in scratch space) confirmed the
         WYSIWYG approach is viable: an automated round-trip test (InvokeScript sets up a
         contenteditable div, programmatically edits it to the exact <figure>/<figcaption>
         markup shape planned for Insert Image, and dispatches an input event; the JS-global
         invokeCSharpAction bridge — auto-injected, no manual setup needed — delivered the
         edited HTML back to C# via WebMessageReceived, byte-for-byte correct) passed cleanly.
         Found and fixed one real, reproducible native crash along the way: attaching a
         NativeWebView to a Window before that window completes a real Avalonia layout pass
         crashes with "Invalid view geometry: y is NaN" inside WKWebView's own init — fixed by
         deferring Window.Content assignment and the first Navigate call to
         Dispatcher.UIThread.Post(..., DispatcherPriority.Loaded). Phase 8 must apply this same
         pattern for both the editor's WYSIWYG pane and PreviewWindow. -->
    <!-- 2.2.0: Phase 1 of the HTML refactor (see 2.0.0 note / the plan doc) — the core storage
         format change. Chapter/front-matter/back-matter body files now use a new ".ebhtml"
         extension instead of ".md" (ProjectPaths, ChapterFileNaming.BuildFileName,
         ChapterFileService.CreateNewChapterFile, OrphanChapterScanner's *.ebhtml glob) — the
         "YAML front matter, blank line, then body" wrapper convention itself is unchanged, only
         the extension and, starting in Phase 2, what the body actually contains. ProjectFile
         gained a CurrentSchemaVersion = 2 constant (1 = legacy Markdown-bodied .md projects, 2 = HTML-
         bodied .ebhtml projects going forward); new projects are created at version 2, but
         loading a version-1 project isn't gated yet — that belongs to the migration tool
         (Phase 6). ChapterImportService now recognizes .ebhtml alongside legacy .md, reusing the
         same front-matter/body parse as before, since Phase 1 doesn't change body content, only
         its extension — needed so OrphanChapterScanner's newly-.ebhtml-aware results can still be
         picked up and imported (a real gap: OrphanChapterScanner found .ebhtml orphans fine, but
         ChapterImportService's extension switch had no case for it and threw). No content-
         generation, import-conversion, or export code touched yet — that's Phases 2 through 5. -->
    <!-- 2.2.1: hotfix, patch bump — the 2.2.0 changelog comment above accidentally contained a
         run of three literal hyphen characters (illustrating the YAML front matter delimiter),
         which is invalid inside an XML comment body and broke every build/restore off
         origin/main with an MSB4024 error. Reworded to avoid consecutive hyphens. No code
         changes otherwise. -->
    <!-- 2.3.0: Phase 2 of the HTML refactor (see 2.0.0 note / the plan doc) — content-generation
         rewrite. PageGeneratorService and BookIndexGenerator (title/imprint/TOC/about-author
         pages, and the internal book.ebhtml navigation index) now emit HTML fragments instead of
         Markdown, and moved out of eBookEditor.Markdown into a new eBookEditor.Html project with
         no Markdig dependency — that project holds only format-neutral generation logic and is
         what survives once eBookEditor.Markdown is retired (Phase 9). Every metadata value
         interpolated into a page (title, author names, bio, disclaimer, etc.) is now
         HTML-encoded via WebUtility.HtmlEncode, a real new correctness requirement Markdown
         generation never needed — confirmed by test (raw "&", "<", ">" in a title no longer
         corrupt the markup) and by the fact that WebUtility.HtmlEncode also escapes apostrophes
         (e.g. the default copyright disclaimer's "author's imagination"), which changed a couple
         of test assertions from raw text to their encoded form without being a functional bug.
         Free-form multi-paragraph text (author bio, disclaimer) is now split into real
         &lt;p&gt;/&lt;br&gt; HTML instead of relying on Markdown's blank-line paragraph
         convention. The in-book TOC's chapter links no longer need Markdown's
         angle-bracket-wrapped-destination workaround for space-containing chapter filenames —
         HTML href attributes handle spaces natively.
         Known, expected regression, deferred on purpose: EpubBuilderTests.
         Build_TocPageLinksResolveToTheChaptersActualContentDocument is now Skip-annotated.
         EpubInternalLinkResolver.RewriteChapterLinks still matches Markdown link syntax
         ("[text](path)") applied to raw file content before Markdig conversion; the generated
         TOC page now emits real "&lt;a href&gt;" HTML instead, so the resolver never matches and
         TOC links point at project-relative source paths instead of EPUB content document
         filenames. Rewriting EpubBuilder/EpubInternalLinkResolver to consume real HTML anchors
         is Phase 4's job ("EPUB export simplification") — fixing it here would mean doing Phase
         4's work inside Phase 2's commit. -->
    <!-- 2.4.0: Phase 3 of the HTML refactor (see 2.0.0 note / the plan doc) — import pipeline
         rewrite. OpenXmlToMarkdownConverter -> OpenXmlToHtmlConverter: same DOM-walking approach
         (bold/italic, H2/H3 subheadings, single-level bullet/numbered lists, inline images,
         hyperlinks, tables), now emitting HTML instead of Markdown, with list-item grouping into
         a wrapping &lt;ul&gt;/&lt;ol&gt; (a new concern HTML has that Markdown's flat "- item"
         lines never needed) tracked by DocxImportService across consecutive paragraphs. Deleted
         HtmlToMarkdownConverter and its ReverseMarkdown NuGet dependency entirely — replaced by
         HtmlImportSanitizer (new AngleSharp dependency), a parse/sanitize/pass-through step
         rather than a format conversion, since the app's own storage format is HTML too now.
         Sanitizing strips &lt;script&gt;/&lt;style&gt; elements, head content, "javascript:"
         URLs, and inline "on*" event handler attributes — a real new security concern once
         imported content renders in a WYSIWYG WebView (Phase 8), not just an editor text box.
         ChapterImportService now routes .ebhtml/.md to the unchanged native pass-through, .docx
         to the new HTML-emitting converter, and .html/.htm to the sanitizer. ChapterDraft and
         ChapterImportDraft's BodyMarkdown property renamed to Body (format-neutral) throughout.
         The "Import Chapters" file picker filter gained "*.ebhtml" alongside the existing
         patterns. Known, expected regression from Phase 2, still deferred: EpubBuilderTests.
         Build_TocPageLinksResolveToTheChaptersActualContentDocument stays Skip-annotated —
         that's Phase 4's fix, not Phase 3's. -->
    <!-- 2.5.0: Phase 4 of the HTML refactor (see 2.0.0 note / the plan doc) — EPUB export
         simplification. EpubBuilder drops its MarkdownToHtmlConverter step entirely (and the
         eBookEditor.Markdown project reference along with it) — the stored HTML body now wraps
         directly into the XHTML shell. EpubInternalLinkResolver and EpubImageResolver rewritten
         to match real HTML ("&lt;a href="..."&gt;", "&lt;img src="..."&gt;") instead of Markdown
         link/image syntax, so the in-book TOC's chapter links and chapter images still resolve
         correctly to the packaged EPUB's own content-document/images layout. The
         EpubBuilderTests test that Phase 2 had to Skip-annotate now passes for real, unskipped.
         Also fixed a real, previously-latent bug this phase's own tests surfaced in
         HtmlXmlSafety (used to make stored HTML valid XHTML before XML-parsing it into the
         content document): its void-element (img/br/hr) self-closing regex excluded "/"
         entirely from the attribute-content group, so any void element with a "/" anywhere in
         an attribute value (e.g. an ordinary "src="../images/x.jpg"" path) was never recognized
         as needing self-closing and broke XML parsing outright. Never manifested before because
         every &lt;img&gt; used to come from Markdig's own already-self-closing HTML renderer;
         this app's own HTML (generators, DOCX/HTML importers) routinely has such paths. -->
    <!-- 2.6.0: new feature, so a minor bump — not one of the HTML refactor's own numbered
         phases, but built on top of it. OrphanChapterScanner now also finds legacy .md, .docx,
         and .html/.htm files sitting untracked in chapters/ (previously only .ebhtml). Every
         non-.ebhtml orphan MainWindowViewModel.ImportOrphanedChapterFiles finds is silently
         converted — imported the same way a drag-and-dropped file would be, written out as a
         brand new native .ebhtml chapter file, added to the spine — and only once that new file
         is safely in place is the original non-native file deleted, so orphan pickup can't
         leave a project with two copies of the same chapter in two formats. -->
    <!-- 2.7.0: new feature, so a minor bump. Chapter file names built by
         ChapterFileNaming.BuildFileName never contain spaces anymore — "023 - What Now.ebhtml"
         is now "023-What-Now.ebhtml". Whitespace runs in the title portion collapse to a single
         hyphen (alongside the existing cross-platform-invalid-character handling), and the
         number/title separator changed from " - " to "-" to match. Plain filesystem hygiene,
         and one less thing to percent-encode wherever a chapter's relative path ends up as an
         HTML href or asset URL (EPUB content documents, the future WYSIWYG editor's WebView).
         ChapterFileNaming.ParseHint (which reads position/title hints back out of a file name)
         is unchanged — it still accepts space, period, hyphen, underscore, or colon as the
         number/title separator, so old space-containing file names remain readable. -->
    <!-- 2.8.0: Phase 5 of the HTML refactor (see 2.0.0 note / the plan doc) — PDF/Word export
         rewrite, the plan's own highest-effort phase, now with real CSS. MarkdownToPdfRenderer
         -> HtmlToPdfRenderer and MarkdownToDocxConverter -> HtmlToDocxConverter both walk an
         AngleSharp DOM instead of a Markdig AST, preserving the existing "switch over node type
         -> emit QuestPDF/OpenXml calls" structure. Pagination itself (roman/arabic numbering,
         verso/recto running headers, clickable TOC via SectionLink) is untouched — only PDF's
         input source changed.
         New shared infrastructure in eBookEditor.Html: HtmlStyleDocument (AngleSharp.Css real
         cascade/specificity/inheritance resolution — verified directly against a spike before
         wiring it in, not assumed to work), CssValueParser (em/%/pt/px length resolution),
         CssColor (hex/rgb()/named-color parsing), HtmlBookAssembler (replaces
         MarkdownExportService's whole-book concatenation for Word's whole-book export), and
         HtmlText.CountWords (fixes a real bug this phase's own tests caught: naively
         whitespace-splitting raw HTML text for a word count miscounts "&lt;p&gt;Hello" as one
         token — used by both PDF and EPUB export). A small user-agent baseline stylesheet
         (strong/em/u/s/mark/sub/sup etc.) is cascaded under the template CSS, since
         AngleSharp.Css has no built-in default stylesheet the way a real browser does.
         EditorStyleCatalog classes (and any other CSS the selected template defines) now
         actually render, not just structurally survive unstyled — confirmed by test, not just
         asserted. Word gets real primitives QuestPDF/PDF simply doesn't have: true small caps
         (w:smallCaps), true letter spacing (w:spacing), true all-caps display (w:caps). PDF
         approximates text-transform: uppercase by uppercasing the text itself, and silently
         skips font-variant: small-caps, letter-spacing, and ::first-letter drop caps — no
         QuestPDF primitive exists for any of them, and an uppercase-text approximation of small
         caps would misrepresent the source styling rather than honestly degrade it.
         Per the user's decision to cut the Markdown export feature: deleted
         MarkdownExportService and the "Export → Markdown (Whole Book/This Chapter)…" menu
         items/commands entirely (MarkdownExportService also happened to power Word's
         whole-book export internally — that's now HtmlBookAssembler instead). Evaluated
         HtmlToOpenXml (the NuGet package) as a Word-side foundation per the plan and decided
         against it: hand-rolling the AngleSharp-DOM-to-OpenXml walk keeps exact control over
         this app's specific formatting/schema-ordering requirements (already a source of real
         past bugs — see the 1.9.1/1.9.3 changelog entries) and keeps the PDF/Word renderers
         structurally consistent with each other, without pulling in an unfamiliar dependency
         mid-refactor.
         Footnotes are deliberately NOT handled in either renderer — there's no HTML authoring
         convention for them yet (no toolbar command produces one), and inventing one in
         isolation here would risk not matching whatever Phase 7's "Insert Footnote" command
         actually produces. Task lists have no HTML authoring convention either and are
         similarly out of scope. Both are documented gaps, not oversights — see
         HtmlToPdfRenderer/HtmlToDocxConverter's own doc comments. Updated the user manual's
         Exporting Your Book chapter to match: removed the cut Markdown export section and the
         now-inaccurate footnote claims, added a note that Apply Style classes render for real
         in PDF/Word now. -->
    <!-- 2.9.0: Phase 6 of the HTML refactor (see 2.0.0 note / the plan doc) — legacy content
         migration tooling. New eBookEditor.Migration project (ProjectMigrator), keeping Markdig
         as a NuGet-only, migration-only dependency for this one-time batch conversion — reusing
         MarkdownToHtmlConverter's existing wrapper rather than hand-rolling parsing for a
         rarely-run tool. Shipped as an explicit, user-triggered "Project -> Upgrade Project to
         HTML..." command (never silent), which backs up the whole project directory first, then
         converts every spine item's Markdown body to HTML verbatim and deletes the old ".md"
         file. Hand-edited generated pages (title/imprint/TOC/about-author) are converted
         verbatim, not regenerated from metadata, so hand-edits survive. Idempotent — safe to
         invoke on an already-migrated project, and NeedsMigration/MigrateToHtml both check the
         actual file extensions on disk rather than trusting ProjectFile.SchemaVersion directly:
         a project.ebookproj.json saved before the SchemaVersion field existed has no
         "schemaVersion" key in its JSON, and System.Text.Json fills an absent init-property
         from its C# default (CurrentSchemaVersion) — trusting the field would make a genuinely
         legacy project look already-migrated.
         Acceptance-tested against real, actively-maintained projects per the plan's own
         criteria: copies of this repo's manual/ project and an external "Test Book" project
         were migrated and re-exported to EPUB/PDF/Word, not the tracked originals. That test
         caught a real, pre-existing bug in Phase 5's HtmlToDocxConverter: every embedded
         image's DrawingML docPr/cNvPr "id" was hardcoded to 1, so any document with more than
         one image produced schema-invalid OOXML (Word refuses such a file) — a bug that only
         ever worked by accident for single-image documents, inherited verbatim from the
         pre-refactor MarkdownToDocxConverter and never caught until a real multi-chapter,
         multi-image book actually exercised the whole-book export path. Fixed by deriving each
         image's id from how many Drawing elements already exist in the document so far, instead
         of a hardcoded constant.
         Updated the user manual's Getting Started chapter: a new "Upgrading an older project"
         section, plus two Phase-5-era inaccuracies caught in passing (the project directory
         description still said "plain Markdown files", and the title-bar-menu tour still listed
         Markdown in the Export menu after Phase 5 cut that feature). -->
    <!-- 2.10.0: Phase 7 of the HTML refactor (see 2.0.0 note / the plan doc) — editor UI
         raw-mode swap. EditorStyleCatalog's EditorStyle record gained an IsBlock flag (six
         inline styles wrap in &lt;span class="..."&gt;, five block styles — Verse, Inset,
         Attribution, Drop Cap, Caption — wrap in &lt;div class="..."&gt;, replacing the old
         "::: {.class} ... :::" custom-container syntax). InsertTableWindow now builds a real
         &lt;table&gt;&lt;thead&gt;...&lt;tbody&gt; with per-column text-align styles instead
         of a GFM pipe-table string, and HTML-encodes cell text. OnInsertImageClick now emits a
         &lt;figure&gt;&lt;img&gt;&lt;figcaption class="caption"&gt; instead of the Phase-
         5-era nested-custom-container workaround. Added a new "Insert Footnote…" command (no
         prior equivalent existed) that inserts a &lt;sup id="fnref:N"&gt;&lt;a href="#fn:N"
         class="footnote-ref"&gt; reference at the cursor and appends/extends a &lt;div
         class="footnotes"&gt;&lt;ol&gt; block at the end of the page — deliberately reusing
         the .footnote-ref/.footnotes/.footnote-back-ref class names DefaultStylesheet.cs
         already defines from the old Markdig-footnote era, so no new CSS was needed. The
         editor's AvaloniaEdit instance now uses AvaloniaEditCore's built-in "HTML" syntax
         highlighting definition instead of Markdown (confirmed no Markdown highlighting was
         ever actually wired in before this, so this is a net-new addition, not a swap). The
         vendored-AvaloniaEdit-to-NuGet-package swap itself is deferred to land together with
         Phase 8, per the plan's own explicit sequencing note. Updated the user manual: Writing
         in the Editor and HTML Syntax Reference (renamed from Markdown Syntax Reference)
         rewritten for HTML authoring and the new Insert Footnote command; Inserting Tables the
         Easy Way updated for HTML table output; Tips/Limitations and Getting Started's stale
         "raw Markdown"/".md"/no-CSS-engine references fixed to match Phase 5/6's real state. -->
    <!-- 2.11.0: Phase 8 of the HTML refactor (see 2.0.0 note / the plan doc) — WYSIWYG
         build-out + Preview window migration, the plan's own highest-risk phase.
         Added Avalonia.Controls.WebView (11.4.0+, the official MIT-licensed native-webview
         backend — WKWebView on macOS — confirmed viable by the Phase 0 spike). New
         HtmlPageShell (eBookEditor.Html) wraps a chapter's HTML body + the book's selected CSS
         template into a standalone document, with a small injected JS bridge
         (window.ebookEditor: setContent/insertHtml/wrapSelection/scrollToFraction/
         appendFootnoteDefinition) — insertHtml/wrapSelection deliberately use real DOM Range
         manipulation, not document.execCommand, per the plan's own reasoning that execCommand
         bets on legacy/deprecated browser behavior.
         The editor pane now has two interchangeable modes over the same underlying HTML: raw
         (existing AvaloniaEdit) and a new "Rich Text" WYSIWYG mode (a contenteditable
         NativeWebView), toggled by a new button — MainWindow's own IsVisible-toggle between the
         two, confirmed safe despite this app's history of AvaloniaEdit-visibility bugs (1.9.x/
         1.10.x) since those turned out to be an unrelated missing ControlTheme registration
         (fixed for good in 1.10.1), not a consequence of toggling visibility itself.
         The right-click-context-menu-only toolbar commands (Insert Table/Image/Footnote, Apply
         Style) didn't reach the WYSIWYG pane (a context menu attached to EditorTextBox
         specifically), so a new mode-agnostic toolbar row was added above the editor, calling
         the same handlers — each now dispatches to either EditorTextBox.Document (raw mode) or
         the WebView's JS bridge (WYSIWYG mode) via a shared InsertAtCursor/InvokeWysiwygScript
         helper pair. Insert Footnote's numbering scan was fixed to read
         ViewModel.Editor.CurrentText instead of EditorTextBox.Text directly, since the latter
         doesn't reflect WYSIWYG edits (only reaches CurrentText via the debounced JS bridge).
         PreviewWindow migrated to the same NativeWebView/HtmlPageShell technology
         (contenteditable="false"), replacing Markdown.Avalonia's MarkdownScrollViewer — real
         CSS-template-styled rendering instead of a second, independent, CSS-blind parser.
         Applied the exact deferred-attach-after-layout pattern the Phase 0 spike found necessary
         (Dispatcher.UIThread.Post(..., DispatcherPriority.Loaded) before first assigning
         Window.Content/NavigateToString) to avoid WKWebView's "Invalid view geometry: y is NaN"
         crash — needed for PreviewWindow (a fresh Window each time) but not the WYSIWYG pane
         embedded in the already-laid-out MainWindow.
         Fixed a real, latent bug while touching this code: SyncEditorTextFromViewModel's
         "skip if already synced" early-return was accidentally also skipping the Preview
         window's content update on every keystroke in raw mode — Preview only ever updated on
         chapter switches, never while actively typing, contrary to what the manual already
         claimed. Separated the two concerns (avoid resetting AvaloniaEdit's caret vs. keep
         Preview/WYSIWYG in sync) so both now update live.
         Removing Markdown.Avalonia (nothing else depended on it once PreviewWindow no longer
         did) is what unblocks completing Phase 7's deferred NuGet swap: eBookEditor.App now
         references the real Avalonia.AvaloniaEdit package directly instead of the vendored
         src/AvaloniaEdit/ project (namespace AvaloniaEditCore -> AvaloniaEdit, App.axaml's
         StyleInclude path updated to match) — confirmed via the assembly's own embedded
         resources that the real package ships the same "HTML" .xshd highlighting definition and
         Themes/Fluent/AvaloniaEdit.xaml theme this app already depended on. The vendored
         src/AvaloniaEdit/ directory itself is now unreferenced but not yet deleted — that's
         Phase 9's job, per the plan's own phase split. Deleted PreviewMarkdownSanitizer (dead
         code the moment Preview stopped using Markdown.Avalonia) and its test.
         Updated the user manual (Writing in the Editor, Getting Started) for the Rich Text
         toggle and the new toolbar; fixed README.md sections this phase's changes made
         literally false (AvaloniaEdit vendoring rationale, the App's editor description, the
         Preview-vs-export-rendering section, the scroll-sync limitation) — the README's
         still-Markdown-era sections from earlier phases (syntax reference, project layout,
         solution-structure rows for eBookEditor.Markdown/DocxImport/ChapterImport) are pre-
         existing debt spun off as a separate follow-up task rather than folded into this
         commit. -->
    <!-- 2.12.0: Phase 9 of the HTML refactor (see 2.0.0 note / the plan doc) — final cleanup,
         completing the refactor. Deleted src/AvaloniaEdit/ entirely (the vendored copy Phase 8
         made unreferenced by swapping eBookEditor.App to the real NuGet package) and removed its
         eBookEditor.slnx entry. Retired eBookEditor.Markdown: its two remaining files
         (MarkdownToHtmlConverter, MarkdownPipelineFactory — both migration-only since Phases 2-5
         moved every other former consumer to HTML) moved into eBookEditor.Migration (the
         project's own csproj already had a comment anticipating exactly this move, from Phase
         6), which now depends on Markdig directly instead of transitively through the retired
         project. MarkdownToHtmlConverterTests moved alongside them into
         tests/eBookEditor.Tests/Migration/, with its comments reworded to describe what they
         actually test now — a legacy project's on-disk Markdown syntax that the migration
         converter must still parse correctly, not (as the comments previously implied) syntax
         any current editor command still produces. Confirmed no source file, .csproj, or the
         .slnx references eBookEditor.Markdown, AvaloniaEditCore, Markdown.Avalonia, or
         ReverseMarkdown anywhere anymore. New feature is minor version is a bit of a stretch here
         (a "new feature" bump per the repo's version-bump policy) but this is a substantial
         structural change (two projects retired, one dependency graph simplified) rather than a
         same-behavior patch, so it gets the same treatment the plan's other phases did.
         Also fixed README.md's solution-structure table: removed the AvaloniaEdit and
         eBookEditor.Markdown rows (both gone), added a row for eBookEditor.Html (added in Phase
         2, never documented) and eBookEditor.Migration (added in Phase 6, never documented). -->
    <!-- 2.12.1: docs-only patch, no code changes — the README.md follow-up spun off by 2.11.0's
         note. Rewrote the intro paragraph, the eBookEditor.Migration/DocxImport/ChapterImport
         solution-structure rows, the project directory layout, and "Importing chapters" for the
         current .ebhtml/HTML content model. Replaced "Markdown syntax" (and its "Applying
         styles"/"Inserting images" subsections) with "HTML syntax", mirroring the conventions in
         the rewritten manual/chapters/004 - Markdown Syntax Reference.md ("HTML Syntax
         Reference"). Updated "Word export" for HtmlToDocxConverter/HtmlBookAssembler. Fixed the
         "Known limitations" custom-containers bullet, which had gone stale the moment Phase 5
         added real AngleSharp.Css cascade resolution to PDF/Word — replaced with the actual
         remaining gaps (no PDF small-caps/letter-spacing primitive, no ::first-letter drop-cap
         support in either engine), per HtmlToPdfRenderer/HtmlToDocxConverter's own doc comments.
         Also corrected the footnotes bullet and the new HTML-syntax section's footnote coverage:
         verified directly against HtmlToPdfRenderer.cs/HtmlToDocxConverter.cs that footnotes are
         NOT specially handled in either renderer (confirmed by their own doc comments, dated
         back to Phase 5/2.8.0, never revisited after Phase 7/2.10.0 added the "Insert Footnote"
         command) — the old README claim of a PDF "Notes" section and real native Word footnotes
         no longer held; the reference/note now render as ordinary superscript text and a
         trailing list, real only in EPUB. -->
    <!-- 2.12.2: patch, no functional change. Suppressed the NU1608 restore warning every
         project carrying an AngleSharp.Css reference has emitted since Phase 5 (2.8.0) —
         AngleSharp.Css 0.17.0 wants AngleSharp 0.17.x, this solution resolves 1.5.1. Already
         verified safe (see 2.8.0's note and eBookEditor.Html's own csproj comment); the warning
         was just noise at this point, not a live signal to keep watching. -->
    <!-- 2.12.3: two user-reported bug fixes, no new features, so a patch bump.
         (1) A chapter's title/subtitle — entered via the sidebar's "Chapter title"/"Chapter
         subheading" fields — never actually rendered anywhere except the whole-book Word
         export. Chapter files store the title only in front matter, never in the body (by
         design — see HtmlBookAssembler's original comment), and HtmlBookAssembler was the only
         place that ever synthesized a "<h1>Chapter N: Title</h1>" heading from it before
         rendering; PdfBuilder, EpubBuilder, single-chapter Word export, and the editor's own
         Preview/Rich Text panes all just rendered the raw stored body, with no heading at all,
         confirmed to predate this session's refactor entirely (traced back through git history
         to the very first commit that added PDF export). Fixed by extracting the shared
         synthesis into a new ChapterHeadingHtml (eBookEditor.Html) and calling it from every
         one of those five places. For Preview/Rich Text mode specifically this required
         restructuring HtmlPageShell: the heading now renders in a sibling element BEFORE
         #content rather than inside it, so it's visible without becoming part of what the
         WYSIWYG bridge reads back into CurrentText on every edit (which would have permanently
         baked the heading into the saved chapter body the next time it synced). Also wired the
         chapter-header "Apply" button (previously Command-bound only) to explicitly refresh
         Preview/Rich Text afterward, since mutating SelectedSpineItem.Title/Subtitle directly
         doesn't touch CurrentText and so wouldn't otherwise trigger a refresh.
         (2) Drop Cap and Attribution ("Apply Style" catalog entries) silently failed to render
         at all, in every format including Preview — a real regression from Vellum Serif's
         source stylesheet, whose selectors (".attribution p::before", ".drop-cap p:first-letter")
         assumed a nested <p> inside the styled block that this app's own Apply Style
         implementation never produces (a flat "<div class='...'>{text}</div>", confirmed by
         reading MainWindow.OnApplyStyleClick directly). Fixed by changing both selectors
         (DefaultStylesheet.cs and "Vellum Serif.css") to apply directly to the wrapping
         element (".drop-cap:first-letter", ".attribution::before") instead of requiring a
         child <p> — Verse/Inset never had this problem since their rules already applied to
         the div itself. PDF still won't show the drop cap (QuestPDF has no ::first-letter primitive at
         all — a separate, pre-existing, documented limitation, not part of this fix) but
         Preview and EPUB now do. -->
    <!-- 2.13.0: new feature, so a minor bump. Restores real native footnote support to PDF and
         Word, which the HTML content-model refactor's PDF/Word rewrite (2.8.0) had deliberately
         left generic ("Footnotes are deliberately NOT handled here" — that phase's own doc
         comments) since no HTML authoring convention existed yet for them at the time; Phase 7
         (2.10.0) later added "Insert Footnote…" but never revisited PDF/Word to special-case
         the convention it produces, so both kept rendering a footnote reference/note as plain
         inline HTML (a superscript link plus a trailing list) — user-reported as a real,
         confusing regression from this app's pre-refactor behavior (verified directly: the old
         MarkdownToDocxConverter/MarkdownToPdfRenderer, still in git history, did have real
         support).
         Word: a "&lt;sup id="fnref:N"&gt;" reference now becomes a real w:footnoteReference run,
         and its matching "&lt;div class="footnotes"&gt;" note moves into a real FootnotesPart
         (visible in Word's own footnote pane) instead of rendering inline in the body — ported
         from the pre-refactor converter's own FootnotesPart-building code, adapted from walking
         a Markdig AST to walking an AngleSharp DOM. This app's own footnote numbering restarts
         at 1 per chapter (by design, each chapter's notes are its own), but Word's FootnotesPart
         needs document-wide-unique ids — HtmlBookAssembler's whole-book export concatenates
         every chapter into one HTML string, so two different chapters' own "id='fn:1'" would
         otherwise collide. Fixed by assigning Word's internal ids by first-reference-appearance
         order (Word displays footnotes by document flow order regardless of the id's numeric
         value, so this doesn't affect what the reader sees) and pairing each reference to its
         definition by matching them within the same "footnotes" section rather than by the raw,
         non-globally-unique "fn:N" string — caught by a real dictionary-key-collision test
         failure against a two-chapter fixture before this fix, not assumed correct.
         PDF: a footnote reference renders as a real superscript number (previously lost its
         superscript positioning entirely — vertical-align isn't an inherited CSS property, and
         the reference sits on a nested <a>, not the <sup> the "font-size: 75%"/"vertical-align:
         super" baseline rule targets), and the matching "footnotes" div now renders as a
         horizontal rule, a bold "Notes" heading, and numbered rows — restoring the exact layout
         MarkdownToPdfRenderer used before the refactor. True per-physical-page footnote
         placement remains out of scope either way (would need a custom pagination engine
         QuestPDF doesn't offer) — notes still collect at the end of whichever chapter/page
         referenced them, same simplification the app has always made.
         Both renderers drop the note's own "&lt;a class="footnote-back-ref"&gt;" arrow when
         rendering its text — Word's footnote pane already provides its own way back to the
         reference, and PDF has no in-document jump target for the arrow to point at either way,
         so showing it there would just be a dead link. -->
    <!-- 2.13.1: user-reported bug fix, no new features, so a patch bump. Preview and Rich Text
         mode were rendering a page's raw front matter YAML block (the delimiter-fenced "title:
         ..." header at the top of every .ebhtml file) as literal visible text at the top of the
         page — caught by a real screenshot of the
         manual's own TOC page. Root cause: EditorViewModel.CurrentText is always the whole raw
         file (front matter included — the raw editor pane is meant to show/edit it directly),
         but Preview/Rich Text mode was pushing CurrentText straight into HtmlPageShell as if it
         were just the body. Fixed by stripping front matter via
         ChapterFileService.ParseChapter(...).Body before every Preview/Rich-Text push (see
         MainWindow.CurrentBodyOnly). Rich Text mode's edit-back path needed the reverse
         operation too: since it now only ever shows/edits the body, folding an edit straight
         back into CurrentText would have overwritten the front matter block entirely on the
         next save — fixed with a new ChapterFileService.ReplaceBody, which swaps in a new body
         while leaving the existing front matter block's exact original text untouched (not
         re-serialized through ChapterFrontMatter, which could reformat it even when nothing the
         user actually touched changed). -->
    <!-- 2.14.0: new feature, so a minor bump. About the Author's "Author photo path" field gets
         a "Browse…" button (see ProjectImagePicker, eBookEditor.App/Services — a new shared
         helper factored out of MainWindow's Insert Image command, which used the identical
         "pick a file, copy it into the project's images/ folder if it isn't there already,
         auto-rename on a name collision" logic inline; MainWindow now calls the shared helper
         too, rather than keeping two copies of the same pattern to drift apart later). Picking a
         file copies it into the project the same way Insert Image already does, and sets
         AuthorPhotoPath to the project-root-relative result — matching how
         PageGeneratorService.GenerateAboutAuthorPage already resolves that path. The text field
         itself still works exactly as before for anyone who'd rather type/edit the path by hand;
         the button is a faster alternative, not a replacement. Cover image path and publisher
         logo path (Copyright & Publishing) have the identical "bare path text field" gap — left
         for a follow-up, since only Author Photo was actually asked for. -->
    <!-- 2.15.0: new feature, so a minor bump. The "Cover image path" and "Publisher logo path"
         fields (Copyright & Publishing) get the same "Browse..." button 2.14.0 added to About
         the Author's Author photo path — the follow-up that release's own changelog note
         flagged as left over. Both reuse ProjectImagePicker.PickAndCopyIntoImagesDirAsync
         unchanged; CopyrightPublishingWindow.axaml.cs gained two click handlers
         (OnBrowsePublisherLogoClick, OnBrowseCoverImageClick) mirroring
         AboutTheAuthorWindow.axaml.cs's OnBrowseAuthorPhotoClick exactly, each setting its
         metadata property to the project-root-relative "images/{fileName}" result. The text
         fields themselves are unchanged and still accept a hand-typed/edited path. -->
    <!-- 2.16.0: two changes bundled together, so a minor bump (the second is a new feature).
         (1) User-reported bug fix: a chapter whose body already opens with its own hand-typed
         "&lt;h1&gt;" (confirmed against this app's own real manual/ project — every one of its
         chapters is authored that way) got a duplicate heading after 2.12.3's "chapter heading
         never rendering" fix, since that fix synthesized one unconditionally from front matter
         regardless of whether the body already had its own. ChapterHeadingHtml.Build now takes
         the chapter's body and skips synthesis when it already opens with an "&lt;h1&gt;" (a
         leading-whitespace-tolerant regex match on the body's start, not a body-wide search —
         an "&lt;h1&gt;" appearing deeper in the content for some unrelated reason shouldn't
         suppress the real heading). Every call site (PdfBuilder, EpubBuilder,
         HtmlBookAssembler, MainWindowViewModel.ExportChapterAsWord, MainWindow's Preview/Rich
         Text push) now passes the body through.
         (2) New feature: every export (EPUB, PDF, Word) now adds a "Created with eBook Editor
         X.Y.Z on yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm" line to the imprint page, immediately before the copyright
         statement (see GeneratedByLine, eBookEditor.Html). Computed fresh at the moment each
         export actually runs, not baked into the stored copyright.ebhtml at front-matter-
         regeneration time — a project can be exported many times between metadata edits, and a
         timestamp frozen at the last regeneration would go stale across every one of them.
         EPUB and whole-book Word both consume the same stored, generically-walked HTML, so both
         locate the "&lt;p&gt;Copyright ©" paragraph GenerateCopyrightPage always produces and
         insert the credit line immediately before it (falling back to leaving a hand-rewritten
         imprint page unchanged if that exact marker isn't found, rather than guessing where to
         inject); PDF renders the imprint page directly from metadata already (bypassing the
         stored HTML entirely, to pin the copyright block to the physical page bottom — see
         2.8.0's note), so it just adds the line as its own QuestPDF text item in the same spot. -->
    <!-- 2.17.0: new feature, so a minor bump. Adds three new kinds of spine item beyond a plain
         numbered chapter: an unnumbered mid-book divider ("Part One", "Part Two" — reuses
         ChapterNumberMode.None, which SpineService.RenumberChapters/every TOC renderer already
         special-cased into exactly this behavior, so no exporter changes were needed), and
         custom, optional front-matter/back-matter pages (Acknowledgements, Preface,
         Dedication… / Afterword, Postscript, Index, Also By the Author…), reusing
         SpineItemType.FrontMatter/BackMatter — already numbered with roman numerals (front) or
         left unnumbered (back) generically by every exporter, since that logic counts "how many
         FrontMatter items sit at the front of the spine," not the 4 fixed generated pages by
         name. New SpineService methods: AddChapterDivider, AddFrontMatterItem/AddBackMatterItem,
         and MoveItem (Up/Down within a group — front/back-matter pages reposition this way
         rather than via drag-and-drop, which stays chapter-only). The sidebar's "+ Add Chapter"
         button became a "+ Add ▾" menu covering all four kinds; the chapter-header rename form
         (previously gated to Type==Chapter only) now also covers custom, non-generated front/
         back-matter pages. DOCX import gained SpecialPageClassifier, recognizing "Part One"-
         style headings and a curated list of front/back-matter titles so they land as the right
         spine item kind automatically instead of every heading becoming a numbered chapter;
         deliberately leaves Introduction/Prologue as regular chapters (commonly numbered in
         real books — guessing wrong silently is worse than the existing safe default). -->
    <!-- 2.18.0: new feature, so a minor bump. Adds a "RoyalRoad" template — a clean, modern
         web-serial look (Open Sans, light-weight headings, left-aligned body text, a blue
         accent color, a dark-blue-accented table treatment) alongside the existing ornate
         "Vellum Serif" template. Typography choices were measured via a browser's computed-
         style inspector against a real RoyalRoad fiction chapter page's rendered CSS — fonts,
         colors, weights, spacing — never copied from that page's own stylesheet source or any
         of its story text. Matches Vellum Serif.css's full selector list one-for-one so it's a
         complete, standalone template; only the selectors genuinely informed by that
         typographic reference differ, everything else (verse/inset/drop-cap mechanics,
         monospace, all-caps, etc.) is unchanged. Open Sans (regular/semibold/bold, Apache 2.0,
         freely embeddable) ships as real font files in the app's fonts/ directory, following
         the exact same @font-face-embedding approach Vellum's Alegreya/Cinzel/Great Vibes
         fonts already use — no code changes needed for it to appear in the template picker or
         get its fonts installed/embedded, since TemplateService/FontService already discover
         and parse any *.css file in templates/ generically. -->
    <!-- 2.19.0: two new features, so a minor bump.
         (1) Stylesheet Preview: a "Preview" button on the Style window's template picker opens
         a standalone Preview window rendering a generated showcase document (TemplateShowcaseHtml,
         eBookEditor.Html) exercising every selector Vellum Serif.css/RoyalRoad.css define —
         headings, paragraphs, a blockquote, lists, a table, a footnote, an image caption, and
         one worked example of each EditorStyleCatalog style class, all original placeholder
         prose — against the template picker's live, uncommitted selection (a new
         MainWindowViewModel.GetTemplateCss(name) method, distinct from the existing
         GetCurrentTemplateCss, which is hardcoded to the saved value), so a candidate template
         can be judged before clicking Save &amp; Regenerate.
         (2) Create Project from ePub: File menu gains "Create Project from ePub…", picking an
         existing .epub file and generating a brand-new project from its metadata, chapters, and
         cover image (new eBookEditor.EpubImport project — EpubPackageReader/EpubNavigationReader
         parse the container/OPF/nav-or-NCX documents without assuming this app's own export
         layout, EpubImportService classifies each item front/chapter/back-matter via nav
         landmarks first and SpecialPageClassifier as a fallback — reused as-is from DOCX
         import — and EpubProjectImporter writes the result to a new project directory).
         Deliberate, documented scope limits: the source EPUB's own CSS isn't imported (new
         projects use this app's own template system), internal cross-chapter hyperlinks are
         left as inert relative links, footnote markup is imported as plain inline HTML
         verbatim, and the source's own table-of-contents/cover-wrapper pages are skipped
         (identified via nav landmarks, not guessed) since title/copyright pages already get
         freshly generated versions from the parsed metadata. The dispatch logic routing an
         imported draft to the right SpineService Add* method/directory (previously private
         methods on MainWindowViewModel, added for DOCX/HTML import) is extracted into a new
         shared SpineImportRouter (eBookEditor.Core), since EPUB import needs the identical
         dispatch before any MainWindowViewModel exists yet — it's still creating the project. -->
    <!-- 2.19.1: two bug fixes, so a patch bump.
         (1) Renaming a custom front/back-matter page via the header title/subheading form
         silently did nothing — the rename form's visibility was widened to cover these pages
         (2.19.0), but SaveChapterHeader itself still had a leftover Type==Chapter-only guard
         clause from before that change, so the save never actually ran for anything but a
         plain chapter. Both the guard and the IsRenamableItemSelected visibility check now
         share one IsRenamable(SpineItem) helper, so they can't drift apart like this again.
         (2) "Add Part Break" always appended the new divider to the end of the chapter list,
         regardless of what was selected. It now inserts immediately after the currently
         selected chapter (or divider — both are Type.Chapter) via SpineService's existing
         positionHint mechanism, falling back to appending at the end when nothing/a non-
         chapter item is selected — matching how a user would expect an "insert" action
         relative to their current position to behave. -->
    <!-- 2.20.0: new feature, so a minor bump. Revisits "Create Project from ePub"'s three
         previously-documented scope limits and actually builds them.
         (1) The source EPUB's own CSS is now imported as a new template: EpubStylesheetImporter
         parses both it and "Vellum Serif.css" via AngleSharp.Css's raw rule API and, for every
         selector Vellum defines, uses the source's declarations if it defines an equivalent
         (exact selector-text match — real EPUBs consistently style plain structural elements
         for baseline readability, while this app's own EditorStyleCatalog classes essentially
         never exist in a foreign EPUB, so those correctly and consistently fall back to
         Vellum's declaration), else keeps Vellum's own. Source-defined custom fonts actually
         referenced by the merged CSS are extracted from the EPUB and embedded the same way
         Vellum's own fonts are; the new template is named after the book and selected
         automatically, written into TemplateService's real runtime templates/fonts
         directories (not the source tree — those are shared, app-wide locations an end user's
         import writes into at runtime).
         (2) Internal cross-chapter hyperlinks are rewritten to point at the new project's own
         chapter files: EpubImportService now normalizes every internal href to a stable,
         OPF-relative form as each chapter is read (a link is relative to the *linking*
         chapter's own directory, not the OPF's — this needs resolving explicitly), and
         EpubProjectImporter rewrites those to final resolved paths in a pass that runs after
         file-name syncing, once every item's real path is known. A link into a specific
         section of another chapter loses that finer targeting (only the chapter-level target
         survives) — a documented limitation, not a bug.
         (3) Footnotes are now best-effort converted into this app's own convention (the exact
         shape "Insert Footnote…" itself authors) via new EpubFootnoteConverter: detects both
         EPUB3-native epub:type="noteref"/"footnote" markup and plain same-page
         sup+fragment-link/id pairs (a reference only pairs with a target that appears later in
         the body — a definition can't precede its own reference). Anything that looks like a
         footnote reference but doesn't resolve gets a real new footnote inserted immediately
         after it reading "TODO: ...please review and fix it manually," rather than being
         silently left broken. -->
    <!-- 2.20.1: two bug fixes, so a patch bump.
         (1) The Recent Projects menu could end up permanently empty: AppSettingsService.Load()
         had no try/catch around its JSON deserialize, and MainWindow.OnRecentProjectsSubmenuOpened
         clears the menu's items *before* calling it — an exception (a corrupt/truncated
         settings.json, plausible since Save() previously wrote directly to the real file with
         no locking between the several AppSettingsService instances, one per open window, that
         all share it) left the menu cleared with neither real entries nor the "no recent
         projects" fallback. Load() now falls back to a fresh AppSettings on any read/parse
         failure instead of throwing; Save() now writes to a temp file and renames it into place
         instead of writing the real file directly, so a mid-write crash can no longer produce a
         truncated file for Load() to trip over next time.
         (2) No relative image (`&lt;img src="../images/foo.jpg"&gt;`) ever displayed in Preview
         or the WYSIWYG editor pane — both navigated the WebView with "about:blank" as the base
         URI, which has no filesystem context for a relative path to resolve against, so every
         chapter's inserted images (not just the About the Author photo that surfaced this) were
         silently broken. New HtmlPageShell.BuildFileBaseUri(projectDirectory) builds a real
         file:// base URI from the project's own directory instead, used by both PreviewWindow
         (which now takes the project directory as a parameter on UpdateContent, since it was
         previously fully decoupled from CurrentProject) and MainWindow's WYSIWYG navigation. -->
    <!-- 2.21.0: new feature, so a minor bump.
         About the Author photo now gets a real caption: AboutAuthorInfo gained PhotoCaption,
         a new "Photo caption" field on the About the Author window (defaults, in the UI's
         watermark text only, to the author's name — the actual fallback logic lives in
         PageGeneratorService.GenerateAboutAuthorPage, computed fresh at generation time from
         metadata.Authors.FirstOrDefault() so it tracks a later author-name edit even if the
         user never typed a caption). The generated page now wraps the photo in
         &lt;figure&gt;/&lt;figcaption class="caption"&gt; instead of a bare &lt;img&gt;, using
         the explicit caption when the user set one, else falling back to the primary author's
         name, and omitting the figcaption entirely when neither is available. -->
    <Version>2.21.0</Version>
  </PropertyGroup>
</Project>
